@neovintage, you're definitely putting the finger on a sore spot of the Airflow infra. We had many talks internally early on about how to do this properly, but there was so many options (flume, fluentd, kafka, s3/hdfs) and I took a shortcut with something that would mostly work for everyone without overthinking or having dependencies on big pieces of infra. 

The right way to go is definitely with an interface and leave it open to be implemented in different ways: BaseLogger + LocalLogger, KafkaLogger, or FluentDLogger, FlumeLogger,...

In the meantime things have been much better than expected with the semi-temporary solution here. We haven't yet lost a worker (but if we did, it would be along with the logs that explains why we lost it...)

@timeisapear: nope, the scheduler still does not fill in gaps, but `backfill` does.

Though it's fairly common to clear downstream and future from the UI, in which case there are no gaps, and the scheduler will move forward.

For context, the main reason why the scheduler does not fill gaps is that it would cost much more to figure out everything that needs to get triggered and put much more load on the database and scheduler. I want to keep this very lean so that we can trigger every minute or so.

@varantz thanks for your contribution! 

After thinking a bit through this it doesn't make sense to insert one row at a time in Vertica (since it's a column store) and the hook's `insert_rows` should probably overridden while using this:
https://pyvertica.readthedocs.org/en/latest/#pyvertica.batch.VerticaBatch.insert_list

